---
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const tags = ['Aviation Networks', 'Transportation Geography', 'World Cup 2026', 'Airline Operations', 'Aviation Resilience'];
---

<Layout
  title="How the 2026 FIFA World Cup Is Stress-Testing America's Air Travel Network"
  description="Aviation demand, hub congestion, and transportation resilience during the largest World Cup in history."
  image={`${base}research/world-cup-network-hero.png`}
  type="article"
>
  <article>
    <header class="article-hero">
      <img src={`${base}research/world-cup-network-hero.png`} alt="An editorial illustration of flight paths connecting airport hubs across North America" />
      <div class="hero-shade"></div>
      <div class="container hero-content">
        <a class="back-link" href={`${base}research`}>&lt;- Research</a>
        <p class="page-kicker">Research Commentary</p>
        <h1>How the 2026 FIFA World Cup Is Stress-Testing America's Air Travel Network</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Aviation demand, hub congestion, and transportation resilience during the largest World Cup in history.</p>
        <div class="byline"><span>Hexin Yu</span><span>June 18, 2026</span><span>10 min read</span></div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="container article-grid">
      <aside class="article-aside">
        <p>Filed under</p>
        <div class="tags">{tags.map((tag) => <span>{tag}</span>)}</div>
      </aside>

      <div class="prose">
        <section>
          <h2>Introduction</h2>
          <p class="standfirst">A World Cup match begins at kickoff, but its transportation footprint begins days earlier and hundreds or thousands of miles away.</p>
          <p>Supporters arrive through international gateways, connect at airline hubs, transfer to hotels, and converge on stadium districts within narrow time windows. In 2026, that movement is distributed across a continent. The tournament is therefore not only a sporting event; it is a large, temporary reorganization of passenger demand across the North American aviation network.</p>
          <p>For aviation research, the important question is not simply whether airports are busy. It is how a burst of event-driven traffic interacts with an already interconnected system during the summer travel peak. Airports, airline schedules, airspace, ground transportation, and hotel capacity form one chain. Pressure at any point can alter passenger flows elsewhere.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Why the 2026 World Cup Is Different</h2>
          <p>The scale is unprecedented: <strong>48 teams, 104 matches, three host countries, and 16 host cities</strong>. FIFA expects 6.5 million stadium spectators, while the United States alone hosts 78 matches. Unlike Qatar in 2022, where venues were concentrated within one small metropolitan region, the 2026 geography stretches from Vancouver to Miami and from Los Angeles to New York/New Jersey.</p>
          <p>That distance changes the role of aviation. A fan following a team may need multiple inter-city flights, not one international round trip plus local transit. Knockout-stage uncertainty makes the pattern harder to forecast because the next destination depends on results. Demand is directional, episodic, and time-sensitive: thousands of passengers may want the same city pair immediately after a match, then leave again within 24 to 48 hours.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="network-figure">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 900 470" role="img" aria-labelledby="fig1-title fig1-desc">
            <title id="fig1-title">2026 FIFA World Cup host city aviation network map</title>
