            </g>
          </svg>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 1.</strong> A schematic view of the tournament's continental geography. Routes illustrate potential inter-city movement rather than scheduled service.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Key Insights from the Video</h2>
          <p>The Bilibili video that prompted this commentary makes four aviation arguments: the tournament's dispersed geography will produce unusual city-pair demand; match-day arrivals and departures will compress traffic into sharp peaks; private aircraft will compete for scarce parking and airspace; and infrastructure expansion alone cannot remove constraints created by staffing, airspace, and aging facilities.</p>
          <p>Those claims are directionally persuasive, but the strongest version of the video's “system overload” framing deserves qualification. Demand is not one national wave. Sojern's April booking analysis found year-over-year growth of 42% for Dallas and 38% for Houston, but a 16% decline for Seattle. Reuters later reported that costly tickets and complex travel kept the expected benefit from materializing evenly for U.S. hotels and airlines. The network is being stressed through concentrated peaks and mismatches, not uniformly saturated.</p>
          <p>For airlines, this creates opportunity and risk at the same time. Extra sections, larger aircraft, and targeted capacity can capture high-yield traffic. Yet tournament demand is temporary and uncertain; aircraft and crews moved toward a match market are unavailable elsewhere. A revenue premium can disappear if ticket costs, visa barriers, or hotel prices suppress travel, or if a team's elimination changes the next wave of bookings.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Air Travel Demand and Host Cities</h2>
          <p>Host cities enter the tournament with different aviation roles. Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston pair matches with global or national hubs. Miami and Los Angeles are major international gateways. New York/New Jersey combines three large commercial airports with the final. Seattle is a geographically peripheral gateway, while Kansas City depends more heavily on connecting flows through other hubs.</p>
          <p>World Cup passengers also behave differently from ordinary leisure or business travelers. Their destination and timing are tied to a fixture; substitution is difficult. Many combine matches across cities, travel in supporter groups, carry national-team schedules rather than flexible itineraries, and book after qualification or knockout outcomes become known. Sojern reported that 65% planned trips of six days or longer, yet its city data varied sharply. Treating “World Cup travelers” as one stable market would hide the network's real spatial pattern.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Hub Airports Under Pressure</h2>
          <p>Hub-and-spoke airlines gather passengers from many origins at a hub, then redistribute them onto onward flights. This creates connectivity that direct service alone cannot provide, but it also couples operations. ATL, DFW, IAH, ORD, DEN, and CLT can carry World Cup passengers even when some are not local match airports: ORD, DEN, and CLT function as transfer points feeding the host-city system.</p>
          <p><strong>The World Cup turns the airline network into a live stress test: when one hub slows down, delays can quickly spread across the system.</strong> A late arrival can create missed connections; holding a departure for connecting fans can delay the aircraft's next leg; displaced passengers consume seats on later flights. Summer thunderstorms, gate conflicts, baggage surges, and crew duty limits can turn a local bottleneck into a network problem.</p>
        </section>

