        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Business Aviation and Airspace Management</h2>
          <p>Commercial passengers are only part of the picture. Teams, sponsors, media crews, executives, and high-value guests also generate charter and private-aviation demand. These flights need slots, customs handling, ramp space, ground services, and parking, often close to the same match windows.</p>
          <p>The FAA's tournament guidance makes the constraint visible. Flight plans may be required six to 24 hours before departure; ground-delay programs can assign precise departure times; and Temporary Flight Restrictions protect stadiums and related sites. In Houston, a Prior Permission Required program covers area airports, including drop-and-go operations. NBAA warns that aircraft without required reservations may be diverted, while Universal Weather highlights parking, permit, and slot pressure across the three-country event. The objective is not simply to move more aircraft. It is to manage finite airspace and surface capacity predictably and safely.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Houston: A First-Hand Observation</h2>
          <p>I attended the Germany versus Curaçao match in Houston on June 14. That made the host city a practical case study rather than an abstract node on a map. Airport activity, downtown activity, transportation demand, and stadium access were parts of the same event system: international visitors entered through the city's gateways, activity collected around central fan spaces, and then a large crowd had to reach Houston Stadium on a fixed schedule.</p>
          <p>The most useful observation was the change in scale across that chain. Airport demand was dispersed across terminals and hours, but stadium demand converged. More than 68,000 people attended, and local reporting estimated that about 20,000 used METRORail's Red Line after the match. Houston absorbed the event through layers of capacity rather than one facility. IAH and Hobby handled access to the region; roads and transit redistributed arrivals; downtown served as an activity center; and the stadium district created the sharpest final bottleneck.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="photo-placeholder">
          <div><span>HY / HOUSTON / 06.14.26</span><strong>Match-day photo placeholder</strong><p>Add a personal photograph showing airport, downtown, transit, or stadium access.</p></div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 3.</strong> Houston match-day observations. Personal image to be added.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Uneven Impacts Across Cities</h2>
          <p>The tournament's aviation effects are spatially uneven because access is uneven. Airfare, hotel supply, match attractiveness, local transit, visa requirements, and the strength of direct international service all shape realized demand. A search does not always become a booking: Sojern found Argentina represented 8.2% of flight searches but only 1.3% of confirmed bookings in its data.</p>
          <p>High ticket and travel costs further filter who can move. Reuters reported weak airline and hotel demand as expensive match tickets and complex last-minute international travel kept some fans away. That does not contradict strong booking growth in Houston or Dallas. It shows that aggregate forecasts can conceal redistribution: one city receives a large pulse while another sees little uplift; one hub captures connections while a peripheral airport sees fewer direct arrivals.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Implications for Aviation Research</h2>
          <p>The World Cup offers a rare dataset for studying aviation networks under a known external shock. Researchers can compare scheduled capacity with realized demand, trace delay propagation from hubs to regional airports, and test whether network centrality predicts disruption exposure. Match schedules provide time-stamped demand events; airport operations and flight performance provide outcomes.</p>
          <p>It also sharpens questions in transportation geography. Does hub dependency help smaller regions reach host cities, or make their trips more vulnerable to missed connections? Do secondary airports absorb business aviation and protect commercial hubs, or simply relocate congestion? Which cities recover fastest after a match-day peak? Interactive route maps and airline network dashboards can make these relationships visible, especially when they combine flight data with weather, airport capacity, and surface transportation.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Conclusion</h2>
          <p>The 2026 World Cup is a real-world experiment in aviation network resilience and large-event transportation management. It creates opportunities for airlines, airports, and cities to serve new flows, but it also exposes hub dependency, parking limits, airspace constraints, and the cost of tightly timed travel.</p>
          <p>The main lesson is not that the U.S. air travel system will uniformly fail or uniformly benefit. The World Cup creates both opportunities and stresses for aviation systems, and its impacts are distributed unevenly across airports, cities, and airline networks. That unevenness is exactly what makes the tournament valuable to study.</p>
        </section>

